To add a vertical divider between `TabBar` tabs in Flutter, you can use the `TabBar`'s `indicator` property along with the `BorderSide` and `VerticalDivider` classes as follows:

```dart
TabBar(
  tabs: [
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 1')),
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 2')),
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 3')),
  ],
  indicator: BoxDecoration(
    border: Border(
      right: BorderSide(
        color: Colors.grey,
        width: 1.0, // adjust width according to your needs
      ),
    ),
  ),
);
```

This will add a 1px wide grey vertical divider between the `TabBar` tabs. You can adjust the color, width, and location of the divider by modifying the `BorderSide` and `indicator` properties as needed.

As a more advanced example, If you want the divider to be animated when the user switches tabs, you can use a custom `TabBarIndicator` widget along with `BorderSide` and `VerticalDivider` classes. Here is an example:

```dart
class CustomTabBarIndicator extends Decoration {
  @override
  BoxPainter createBoxPainter([VoidCallback? onChanged]) {
    return _CustomPainter(
      onChanged,
      borderSide: BorderSide(color: Colors.grey, width: 1.0),
    );
  }
}

class _CustomPainter extends BoxPainter {
  final VoidCallback? onChanged;
  final BorderSide borderSide;

  _CustomPainter(this.onChanged, {required this.borderSide});

  @override
  void paint(Canvas canvas, Offset offset, ImageConfiguration configuration) {
    final rect = Offset(offset.dx, (configuration.size?.height ?? 0) - 2);
    final end = Offset(offset.dx + configuration.size!.width, rect.dy);
    final paint = borderSide.toPaint();
    canvas.drawLine(rect, end, paint);
  }
}

TabBar(
  tabs: [
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 1')),
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 2')),
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 3')),
  ],
  indicator: CustomTabBarIndicator(),
);
```

This will create a vertical divider that animates between `TabBar` tabs using a custom painter. `CustomTabBarIndicator` extends the `Decoration` class and creates a custom `BoxPainter` that draws a line along the right edge of the active tab.

To disable the bar under the `TabBar` when a tab is selected in Flutter, you can use the `indicator` property and set its height to 0. Here is an example:

```dart
TabBar(
  tabs: [
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 1')),
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 2')),
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 3')),
  ],
  indicator: BoxDecoration(
    border: Border(
      bottom: BorderSide(
        color: Colors.transparent,
        width: 0.0,
      ),
    ),
  ),
  onTap: (index) {
    // handle tab tap
  },
);
```

In this example, the `TabBar`'s `indicator` property is set to a `BoxDecoration`, which has a `Border` property that includes a `bottom` `BorderSide`. The `color` and `width` properties of the `BorderSide` are set to `Colors.transparent` and `0.0`, respectively, which effectively disables the bar under the selected tab. 

Keep in mind that by disabling the bar, it may be harder for users to identify which tab is currently selected. Consider using an alternate approach, such as changing the color of the selected tab or adding an indicator icon to the selected tab.

To remove the default `indicator` under the `TabBar` in Flutter, you can set the `indicator` property of the `TabBar` to `null`. Here is an example:

```dart
TabBar(
  tabs: [
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 1')),
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 2')),
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 3')),
  ],
  indicator: null,
  onTap: (index) {
    // handle tab tap
  },
);
```

By setting `indicator` to `null`, the default indicator under the tab bar will be removed, resulting in a cleaner look for the `TabBar`. If you want to customize the indicator, you can replace `null` with a custom decoration, such as `BoxDecoration` with a `BorderSide` or a `TabBarIndicatorSize` like `TabBarIndicatorSize.label`.

Note that by removing the indicator, it may be harder for users to identify which tab is currently selected. Consider using an alternative approach, such as changing the color of the selected tab or adding an indicator icon to the selected tab.

If setting the `indicator` property to `null` doesn't work to disable the indicator in the `TabBar` in Flutter, you can try instead setting the `indicatorSize` property to `TabBarIndicatorSize.label`. Here's an example:

```dart
TabBar(
  tabs: [
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 1')),
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 2')),
    Tab(child: Text('Tab 3')),
  ],
  indicatorSize: TabBarIndicatorSize.label,
  onTap: (index) {
    // handle tab tap
  },
);
```

In this example, `indicatorSize` is set to `TabBarIndicatorSize.label`, which effectively disables the indicator by setting it to the same size as the label text. This will result in a cleaner look for the `TabBar`.

